At Jackson Hole, Chairman Powell invoked Volckerâ€™s name twice directly, twice indirectly. Todayâ€™s COVID-supply-shock inflation is nothing like the â€˜70s inflation that started with â€œguns and butterâ€ in 1964, and accelerated after Nixon ended the gold-exchange standard in 1971.

The Fed is basing monetary policy decisions on lagging indicators: employment and core inflation. Leading inflation indicators like gold and copper are flagging the risk of deflation. Even the oil price has dropped more than 35% from its peak, erasing most of the gain this year.
